\begin{abstract}
The total energy emitted by the growth of massive black holes is large
and can be 10-50 per cent of that emitted by stars in the universe. I
show how the X-ray Background provides a good measure of this energy
and also why most accretion power is absorbed and re-emitted in the
far infrared band. A model for the obscured growth of massive black
holes is presented which accounts for both the high absorption and the
observed black hole to galaxy spheroid mass correlation. Future
missions should detect the obscured X-ray sources associated with the
growth of massive black holes.
